structure.\n\nGaps:\n\n1. **Backup and Disaster Recovery**: \n   - No backup strategy mentioned. If server dies, data loss and downtime.\n   - P1 (high risk of business disruption)\n   - Fix: Infrastructure action (setup backup system) and possibly code (scripts for backup).\n\n2. **Incident Response Plan**:\n   - None mentioned. In case of breach, no defined procedure.\n   - P1 (high risk of mishandling incidents)\n   - Fix: Organizational action (create plan, train staff).\n\n3. **Supply Chain Vulnerabilities**:\n   - No audit of npm packages or Cargo crates for vulnerabilities.\n   - P1 (high risk due to known vulnerabilities in dependencies)\n   - Fix: Code (integrate vulnerability scanning in CI).\n\n4. **Centralized Logging/SIEM**:\n   - Logs are not centralized. Fleet monitor checks but doesn't aggregate logs for analysis.\n   - P2 (medium risk, harder to detect attacks without correlation)\n   - Fix: Infrastructure (set up log aggregation) and code (send logs to central system).\n\n5. **Network Security (WiFi isolation, ARP, DNS)**:\n   - WiFi isolation not done -> customers can attack each other.\n   - ARP spoofing and DNS poisoning possible -> man-in-the-middle attacks.\n   - P1 (high risk for customer data and system integrity)\n   - Fix: Infrastructure (configure network devices for isolation, ARP inspection, secure DNS).\n\n6. **Physical Security (USB, boot control)**:\n   - USB ports and boot from USB not controlled -> someone can plug in malware.\n   - P1 (high risk of introducing malware)\n   - Fix: Physical/Infrastructure (BIOS settings, disable USB ports physically or via policy).\n\n7. **Insider Threat**:\n   - Lack of audit trails for staff actions (except WhatsApp finding, but likely systemic). \n   - P1 (high risk of malicious staff actions going undetected)\n   - Fix: Code (implement logging of staff actions) and infrastructure (store logs securely).\n\n8. **SSL/TLS Certificates**:\n   - Not checked. Risk of expired certs or weak configuration