ysical access control to the venue.\n    - P2 (medium risk, unauthorized physical access)\n    - Fix: Physical (door access control).\n\n18. **Entire Systems: Printers**:\n    - If used, may be an attack vector (network printers).\n    - P3 (low risk, but can be exploited)\n    - Fix: Infrastructure (secure printer config).\n\n19. **Cloud VPS Security**:\n    - Only Tailscale mentioned. What about cloud provider security groups, IAM roles, etc.?\n    - P1 (high risk, cloud misconfigurations common)\n    - Fix: Infrastructure (audit cloud config).\n\n20. **Social Engineering and Phishing**:\n    - Not audited. Staff may fall for phishing, compromising credentials.\n    - P2 (medium risk, requires training)\n    - Fix: Organizational (training).\n\n21. **Denial of Service**:\n    - Not audited. WiFi or server could be overwhelmed.\n    - P2 (medium risk, availability impact)\n    - Fix: Infrastructure (DoS protection).\n\n22. **Firmware Security**:\n    - Devices (pods, NVR cameras) may have vulnerable firmware.\n    - P1 (high risk, devices can be compromised)\n    - Fix: Infrastructure (update firmware).\n\n23. **Mobile App (PWA) Security**:\n    - Part of frontend, but not specifically audited for mobile threats (e.g., insecure storage).\n    - P2 (medium risk)\n    - Fix: Code (audit PWA security).\n\n24. **ISP-level Risks**:\n    - Not audited. DDoS, BGP hijacking. Hard to control but should assess.\n    - P3 (low risk, but can have high impact)\n    - Fix: Organizational (choose reliable ISP, consider DDoS protection).\n\nNow, list comprehensively:\n\nGaps:\n\n1. Backup and disaster recovery plan: P1, infrastructure action.\n2. Incident response plan: P1, organizational action.\n3. Supply chain vulnerability scanning (npm, Cargo): P1, code (CI integration).\n4. Centralized logging/SIEM: P2, infrastructure and code.\n5. WiFi isolation: P1, infrastructure.\n6. ARP spoofing protection: P1, infrastructure.\n7. DNS poisoning protection: P2, infrastructure.\n8. USB po